    <h2>Principles</h2>

    <ul>
      <li>Maintain your alignment, then disrupt your opponent's alignment</li>
      <li>Exert continuous strategic pressure against your opponent</li>
      <li>Control your center of gravity and momentum, have a mobile base</li>
      <li>Continually off-balance your opponent (kuzushi)</li>
      <li>Take a dominant angle</li>
      <li>Attain inside channel control</li>
      <li>Use every part of all your limbs</li>
      <li>Use your head to frame, wedge, and post (free up your arms)</li>
      <li>Your spine can be a powerful frame</li>
      <li>Maintain knee-elbow connection</li>
      <li>Address the leading edge</li>
      <li>
        Meet or redirect (apply force from a different angle; or reduce pressure
        and collapse the frame) your opponent’s force vector
      </li>
      <li>Turn your opponent’s frames into levers</li>
      <li>Use overwhelming force when attacking levers</li>
      <li>
        Maximize control using lever-based control and far-side limb control
        (rotational control)
      </li>
      <li>
        Maximize strength using ratchet levers and internal/external rotation
      </li>
      <li>Focus your force into a small, hard surface area</li>
      <li>Advance position using placeholders</li>
      <li>
        Stay on your side for stronger lateral movement (your body is stronger
        on the sagittal plane)
      </li>
      <li>
        Balance between applying pressure and maintaining base: tight with
        proximal extremities (knees, elbows), wide with distal extremities
        (feet, hands)
      </li>
      <li>Move yourself if you can’t move your opponent</li>
    </ul>

