    <table>
      <caption>Phases of Guard</caption>

      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th scope="col" style="width: 120px"></th>
          <th scope="col">Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Engagement</th>
          <td>
            In seated guard:
            <ul>
              <li>Don’t reach your arms out</li>
              <li>
                Grab the closest part of your opponent (e.g., their fingers)—if
                you reach for their sleeve, they’ll be able to grip you
              </li>
              <li>
                Use your grips on their hands to clear the way so you can grip
                their collar, the back of their head, or their arm 2-on-1
              </li>
              <li>
                Grip progression: fingers → sleeve or wrist (lever to shoulder)
                → collar or head (lever to torso)
              </li>
              <li>
                If your opponent is able to grip you, grip-match them (don’t let
                them grip you for free, battle for an advantage)
              </li>
            </ul></td
          >
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Maintenance</th>
          <td>
            In seated guard:
            <ul>
              <li>
                Block your opponent’s leading edge (the knee if they’re standing
                and circling you) with your hand, post with your other hand, and
                continually adjust your angle to face your opponent, switching
                your hips and the framing arm when necessary
              </li>
              <li>
                From here, you can pull to another guard (e.g., shin-to-shin, De
                La Riva, tripod)
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Retention</th>
          <td>
            In seated guard:
            <ul>
              <li>
                If your opponent is in front of you and their knee starts
                collapsing your straight arm (turning your frame into a lever),
                shorten it to an elbow frame to turn the lever back into a frame
              </li>
              <li>
                If your opponent has a dominant angle and their knee starts
                collapsing your straight arm, don’t turn to face them (turning
                in will give up the guard pass)
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    Half Granby: As your blocking frame starts collapsing,
                    collapse your posting arm (arm frame → elbow frame →
                    shoulder frame) and put your shoulder to the mat so that
                    you’re lying sideways and turned away from your opponent,
                    giving your framing arm room to straighten.
                  </li>
                  <li>Hip escape:</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>
                Frame against the leading edge (often the knee/shin or
                shoulder/upper arm), then mobilize your hips to reset your angle
              </li>
              <li>
                If your hips get turned, maintain posture by turning your torso
                to match
              </li>
            </ul>

            In recumbent guard:
            <ul>
              <li>
                Use knee-elbow connection to prevent guard passes (adjust your
                elbow placement based on the situation—e.g., protecting against
                a knee wedge versus an underhook)
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <table>
      <caption>Open Guards</caption>

      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th scope="col" style="width: 120px"></th>
          <th scope="col">Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th scope="row">General</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                Tends to be good for lighter grapplers since you can manage
                distance with your legs
              </li>
              <li>
                In the engagement phase, start in seated guard so you can grip
                fight—once you establish good grips or feel threatened, switch
                to a recumbent guard so you can engage your legs more
              </li>
              <li>
                Upper body controls tend to facilitate: posture control,
                overhead sweeps, sideways sweeps, triangle, omoplata
              </li>
              <li>
                Lower body controls tend to facilitate: inversions, back takes,
                sit-up sweeps, leg entanglements
              </li>
              <li>
                Heuristics for taking upper body controls on your opponent: if
                they’re leaning forward with their feet far from you; if they’re
                controlling your legs
              </li>
              <li>
                Heuristics for taking lower body controls on your opponent: if
                they’re posturing tall; if they step in with their leg; if
                they’re maintaining strong knee-elbow connection
              </li>
              <li>
                Heuristics for retaining guard versus attacking: if your
                opponent has good grips on your legs; if you can’t bring both
                your legs in front of you
              </li>
            </ul>

            Guard retention
            <ul>
              <li></li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Seated Guard</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>Feet close together</li>
              <li>
                Hands above your feet, not behind (your hands are your first
                layer of defense)
              </li>
              <li>
                Elbows framed inside your shins to maintain knee-elbow
                connection and block your opponent from gripping your pants
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Collar Sleeve Guard</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                Same-side sleeve grip + cross-collar grip—ideally with foot on
                hip (same side as collar/sleeve control) + foot on bicep
              </li>
              <li>
                Links well with: De La Riva guard, spider guard, lasso guard,
                closed guard
              </li>
              <li>Primary attacks: triangle, omoplata</li>
              <li>
                Foot on hip breaks your opponent’s posture and helps push their
                body to stretch their arm out
              </li>
              <li>
                Only place your foot on their hip if you have the collar grip
                (posture control) and sleeve grip (prevents your opponent from
                gripping your leg) and you’re close enough to bring their hand
                past your hips once you fall to your side (to prevent your
                opponent having knee-elbow connection and parrying your leg with
                their hand)
              </li>
              <li>
                Grip the collar slightly above the collarbone and then pull down
                (makes it harder for your opponent to posture up)
              </li>
              <li>
                Push the collar and pull the sleeve to separate your opponent’s
                arm from their body
              </li>
              <li>
                When shooting your foot onto their hip, scoot slightly to the
                opposite side so you can shoot your foot through the gap between
                their arm and leg without your opponent blocking you
              </li>
              <li>
                If you can’t grab both the collar and sleeve, double up on the
                one you’ve got
              </li>
              <li>
                If you’re double-gripping the collar and have broken their
                posture forward, shoot your hips in and shoot your feet outside
                and over their arms onto their biceps—you can then use your leg
                to try to access their arm—if your opponent grips your leg, you
                can grip their sleeve and then you can pummel your foot under
                and outside their bicep and kick your foot forward to break
                their grip
              </li>
              <li>
                If you’re double-gripping their sleeve and they’re posturing up,
                shoot your hips in and shoot your feet outside and over their
                arms (on the gripped arm, put your outstep on their shoulder—on
                the other arm, put your foot on their bicep). Curl your leg down
                and pull your elbows back toward your sides to pull their arm
                down so you can reach for their collar.
              </li>
              <li>
                The double-grip entry strategies from kneeling can also be used
                from standing (especially if you’re in a rush to get to the
                position and don’t have time to establish better grips)
              </li>
              <li>
                From standing: grip their collar and sleeve, pull your elbow in
                tight to your body and step toward the non-controlled side to
                pull their arm away from their body. Step out with your leg
                toward the non-controlled side to give you space to drop to your
                hip on the controlled side and put your foot on their hip. Then,
                bring your other foot over their arm and onto their bicep and
                extend your leg to stretch your opponent’s arm back.
              </li>
              <li>
                Variation: If you have collar and sleeve grips and the leg on
                the same side is on their bicep, lift your hips and rotate
                toward the opposite side, then take your foot off the bicep and
                pendulum it to bring your hips toward their leg and then wrap
                the leg with a De La Riva hook.
              </li>
              <li>
                Pummeling your legs outside and over their arms as you shoot in
                prevents your opponent from blocking your feet
              </li>
              <li>
                If you’re in seated guard and your opponent is trying to grip
                your pants, underhand grip both their sleeves and then shoot
                your hips in and pummel your feet outside and over their arm
                onto their biceps, then establish your collar grip and De La
                Riva hook
              </li>
              <li>
                From closed guard: Grip their sleeve and open your elbow out and
                high (parallel to the floor) to pull their arm taut and prevent
                them from pulling it back. Cross-grip their collar and push it
                away to stretch their arm out. Pinch your knees to maintain
                pressure as you hip out and put the other shin into their armpit
                and across their chest so your opponent can’t get their arm
                inside and block your leg. Use your knee shield to apply
                pressure as you extend your chest and head away, then put your
                foot in their hip. Then move your hips away, then extend your
                upper body away and stretch your opponent forward, then put your
                foot on their bicep.
              </li>
              <li>
                Collar sleeve is advantageous against a kneeling opponent (hard
                for them to prevent you from putting your foot on their hip and
                stretching them and separating their arm from their body)—they
                should stand
              </li>
              <li>
                Don’t shoot the bicep leg for the triangle if their elbow is
                connected to their knee (they’ll likely be able to pass under
                the leg)
              </li>
              <li>
                If your opponent steps over your bicep leg into headquarters,
                frame with your collar hand and put your other foot in front of
                them and push away so you can circle the trapped leg inside and
                recover it onto the bicep
              </li>
              <li>
                Break their posture by pulling down on their collar so they
                can’t pummel their arm inside your bicep leg
              </li>
              <li>
                Can also angle your heel close to their armpit to make pummeling
                hard
              </li>
              <li>
                If your opponent pummels their hand inside your leg, you must
                pummel your leg to recover
              </li>
            </ul>

            <ul>
              <li>
                Primary sequence: Cross-grip your opponent’s collar at their
                collar bone (grants pull/push control and works as a frame).
                Grip their sleeve and pull their arm away from their body by
                rowing your elbow back and locking it at your hip. Fall to your
                side (to the gripped collar side) and put one foot on their hip
                and pummel the other foot onto their bicep. Stretch their arm by
                pushing their hip with your foot and extending your body. Put
                your knee inside their outstretched arm. Pull your opponent
                forward as you lift your hips and shoot into the triangle.
              </li>
            </ul>

            Attacks
            <ul>
              <li>
                Triangle (kneeling opponent): From collar sleeve position, pull
                their arm away from their body by getting up on your elbow,
                shoot your hips in slightly so you can bring your chest forward
                next to your elbow, and then extending and rotating your chest
                with your elbow locked tight to your side (stretches their arm
                forward), then open your elbow (brings their arm out). Repeat
                this process until you can put your knee inside their elbow.
                Then, pull your hips in, then pull your opponent forward
                (lifting up with your elbows) as you shoot your legs up and
                establish a triangle. Make sure your hips end up past their
                elbow line.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
