    <table>
      <caption>Clamp-Based Guards</caption>

      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th scope="col" style="width: 120px"></th>
          <th scope="col">Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Closed Guard</th>
          <td>
            Entry
            <ul>
              <li>
                To enter closed guard, your opponent must have space between
                their arm and body

                <ul>
                  <li>Put your foot on their hip and pry their arm away</li>
                  <li>
                    Off-balance them to get them to put their hands on the mat
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>
                Open guard entry: Control one arm (collar sleeve grip or
                two-on-one grip) and put your foot on the hip on the same side.
                Then fall to the controlled side (post on your elbow if using a
                sleeve grip) and pull their arm. Hook your other leg under their
                armpit, keeping your knee and shin tight against them (to
                prevent them from pummeling their arm in), then pull yourself
                into closed guard.
              </li>
              <li>
                If your opponent is in combat base (knee-elbow connection while
                kneeling or standing): put your foot on their bicep on the
                trailing side, rotate toward the trailing side and pummel your
                shin onto their leading shin (hook the inside of their ankle).
                Stretch wide with your legs: extend your leg to separate their
                knee from their elbow as you push outward and into and then past
                their bicep with your other leg, then pull into closed guard.
              </li>
              <li>
                From half guard with a low knee shield: Overhook and pull their
                shoulder in tight to your body. Use a C-grip on your opponent’s
                wrist to strip their grip (if any) from your bottom leg, then
                frame it with a straight arm and turn your C-grip outward (so
                the gap is facing away from you). then extend your body,
                stretching your opponent out by pushing with your knee as you
                arch back. Retract your bottom leg, reach it past their hip, and
                use it to pull yourself into closed guard.
              </li>
            </ul>

            Breaking posture
            <ul>
              <li>
                Pull your knees toward your chest—curl your legs in to keep your
                hips tight against your opponent’s hips
              </li>
              <li>Pull their collar down</li>
              <li>Pull their arm forward and across</li>
              <li>
                If your opponent is framing on your body by gripping your lapel,
                break the grip (two-on-one) then pull their arm forward and
                across; or collapse their elbow by pressuring down on their
                forearm just below the elbow with your forearm while your other
                hand pulls with a cross-collar grip
              </li>
              <li>
                Once their posture is broken, control their head (hook your arm
                on their traps below their neck)
              </li>
            </ul>

            Getting the arm across
            <ul>
              <li>
                You want to get their elbow past your midline and then break
                their posture
              </li>
              <li>
                Usually, you’ll want to use a combination of pushing their arm
                across and moving your hips out to the side
              </li>
              <li>
                If your opponent has a same-side grip on your lapel, you need to
                break their grip: cross-grip their sleeve and then figure-four
                grip your wrist under their arm, then push away from where
                there’s a gap between their fingers and thumb (e.g., push
                straight up). After the grip has been stripped, maintain the
                cuff grip and with your other hand grip over their fingers so
                they can't regrip. Then, loop your cuff grip over the top of
                their hand so your cuff-gripping wrist is blocking their wrist.
              </li>
              <li>
                Get 2-on-1 control (tricep + sleeve/wrist), then pull their arm
                up and across your body (in a wide arcing motion to bring them
                forward and maximally turn their body) as you bring your knees
                to your chest
              </li>
              <li>
                In no-gi, grip their wrist with the gap between your thumb and
                fingers facing toward you (so your opponent can’t slip out by
                pulling toward themselves—if they try to slip out by pushing
                toward you, that helps you bring their arm across)
              </li>
              <li>
                Once you start to angle out from under your opponent to take
                their back, make sure their posture stays broken: put an arm
                over and grab their opposite armpit, and keep control over the
                arm you pulled across and stretch it out (frame it with your
                straight arm parallel to the floor). Drive your chest tight
                against their tricep before you try to take the back. It’s
                crucial to make sure they can’t free their elbow. Post on your
                elbow (slide your elbow in an upward and outward arc to bring it
                beside you). Hook your top leg on their opposite hip, then
                bridge into your opponent as you pull yourself to the back (the
                bridge can make them open their opposite elbow to post, freeing
                your bottom leg), maintaining pressure the whole time to prevent
                your opponent from freeing their elbow. Connect your hands with
                two underhooks to prevent sliding forward over your opponent’s
                head.
              </li>

              Responses to standing up
              <ul>
                <li>
                  If your opponent has their hands on your biceps: circle your
                  hands under their forearms and follow through with your
                  forearms and elbows to strip their grips as you bring your
                  knees to your chest to pull them forward
                </li>
                <li>
                  If your opponent has their hands on your biceps and you can’t
                  circle your arms in: side crunch to extend one side of your
                  body as you stretch your arm on that side away from your
                  opponent. Grab their wrist with the other hand, then go back
                  to your regular position (controlling their hand so it can’t
                  go back on your bicep) and grab behind their tricep (tricep
                  and wrist control).
                </li>
                <li>
                  A great time to break posture is as your opponent is standing
                  up (if they’re not framing on your chest or biceps with their
                  arms)—pull them forward with your legs as they take their knee
                  off the ground, removing their base on that side
                </li>
                <li>
                  If your opponent starts standing and puts one leg up, crunch
                  to that side and underhook the leg. Then, uncrunch and pull
                  the leg straight and bring it close to your body. When your
                  opponent moves forward to bend their leg, you can break their
                  posture.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If your opponent is able to start opening your legs, open your
                  guard proactively: cuff-grip their sleeves (strip their grip
                  on your leg if you can), bring your knees inside, and put your
                  feet on their hips inside their arms with your legs flared
                  out. From here, you can pull their arms forward and pull back
                  into closed guard.
                </li>
              </ul>

              Sweeps
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Lumberjack sweep (opponent is in a staggered stance):
                  Underhook their leading ankle, putting it in the crook of your
                  elbow and pulling your bicep and shoulder in tight toward the
                  leg. Drop your hips, arch your head away, and push into the
                  inside of their thigh with your hip (optionally, push off the
                  mat with your free arm to exert more force) to bring your
                  opponent down sideways. After the sweep, keep the bottom leg
                  controlled and get into mount (if they fall on the opposite
                  side, control their posture and stay in closed guard).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Back sweep (opponent is in a square stance): Grip their
                  ankles, open your legs and drop your hips, then push your
                  opponent backward with your calves. As soon as they’re
                  falling, sit up and reach for their collar or head, and post
                  on the mat so you can get up first and get into mount.

                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      If your opponent leans forward to prevent the sweep, shoot
                      your hips up and grab their head to reestablish closed
                      guard with their posture broken.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>
